{"title_page": "Dachau liberation reprisals", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Reprisals against Germans during the liberation of Dachau}}\nDuring the '''Dachau liberation reprisals''', German prisoners of war were killed by U.S. soldiers and concentration camp internees at the [[Dachau concentration camp]] on April 29, 1945, during [[World War II]]. It is unclear how many [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] members were killed in the incident but most estimates place the number killed at around 35\u201350.  In the days before the camp's liberation, SS guards at the camp had  forced 7,000 inmates on a [[Death marches (Holocaust)|death march]] that resulted in the death of many from exposure and shooting.<ref name=\"USHM --- death marches\">{{cite web|title=Death Marches|url=https://www.ushmm.org/outreach/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007734|website=www.ushmm.org|publisher=U.S. Holocaust Museum|accessdate=March 4, 2018|language=en}}</ref> When Allied soldiers [[Dachau concentration camp#Liberation|liberated Dachau]], they were variously shocked, horrified, disturbed, and angered at finding the massed corpses of internees, and by the combativeness of some of the remaining guards who allegedly fired on them.\n\n==Discoveries==\n[[File:Dead corpses in train dachau.jpg|thumb|Corpses of internees who were left by their Nazi guards to die in a train at Dachau. Thousands of prisoners were murdered by the Nazis in the days before the camp's liberation.]]\n[[File:Kz dachau liberation person.jpg|thumb|SS men confer with General [[Henning Linden]] during the capture of the Dachau concentration camp. Pictured from left to right: SS aide, camp leader Untersturmf\u00fchrer Heinrich Wicker (mostly hidden by the aide), [[Paul M. G. L\u00e9vy]], a Belgian journalist (man with helmet looking to his left), Dr. Victor Maurer (back), Gen. Henning Linden (man with helmet, looking to his right) and some U.S. soldiers.]]\n\nOn April 29, 1945, soldiers of the 3rd Battalion, 157th Infantry Regiment, 45th Infantry Division, commanded by Lieutenant Colonel [[Felix L. Sparks]], approaching the sprawling Dachau complex from the southwest, found 39 railway [[boxcar]]s containing some 2,000 skeletal corpses parked on rail tracks just outside the complex itself. Brain tissue was splattered on the ground from one victim found nearby with a crushed skull. The smell of decaying bodies and human excrement, and the sight of naked, emaciated bodies induced vomiting, crying, disbelief, and rage in the advancing troops.<ref name=\"US Holocaust Museum \u2013 Dachau\">{{Cite web|url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/dachau|title=Dachau|website=encyclopedia.ushmm.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Dachau, May Day, 1945\">[http://www.evesmag.com/dachau.htm \"Dachau, May Day, 1945\"], Eve's Magazine</ref><ref name=\"The Liberator 2012. page 273, 274\">The Liberator : One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. page 273, 274</ref> Advancing soldiers from H Company, 22nd Regiment used a loudspeaker to call on the SS to surrender, but they continued to fire in bursts.<ref>Corporal Robert W. Flora, H Company, 22d Regiment Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 76.</ref><ref>Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 101</ref>\n\nUpon moving deeper into the complex, and the prisoner area itself, the soldiers found more bodies. Some had been dead for hours and days before the camp's capture and lay where they had died. Soldiers reported seeing a row of concrete structures that contained rooms full of hundreds of naked and barely clothed dead bodies piled floor to ceiling, a coal-fired crematorium, and a gas chamber.<ref name=\"Dachau and Its Liberation, by Felix L. Sparks\">{{Cite web|url=http://45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm|title=Dachau|website=45thinfantrydivision.com|access-date=April 1, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217085000/http://www.45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm|archive-date=February 17, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"The stench of death was overpowering,\" Sparks recalled.<ref>The Liberator : One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. pages 281, 282</ref>\n\n==Surrender==\nAccording to [[Harold Marcuse]], an American professor of German history, the camp commander SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer [[Martin Gottfried Weiss|Martin Weiss]], together with the camp guards and the SS garrisons, had fled the camp before the arrival of U.S. troops. SS-[[Untersturmf\u00fchrer]] Heinrich Wicker (killed after the surrender) was left in charge and had roughly 560 personnel at his disposal; these came from conscripted inmates of the SS disciplinary prison inside the Dachau concentration camp and Hungarian [[Waffen-SS]] troops.<ref>Harold Marcuse, ''Legacies of Dachau: The uses and abuses of a concentration camp'', 1933\u20132001, p.52</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 1945 Dachau was surrendered to [[Brig. Gen.]] [[Henning Linden]] of the [[42nd Infantry Division (United States)|42nd Infantry Division]] of the U.S. Army by Untersturmf\u00fchrer Wicker. According to Linden, he arrived at the command post in Dachau at about 15:00 and proceeded to make his way across the Amper River to the site of the complex approximately one-half kilometer south of the bridge he crossed.<ref>Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. p 14. Text from May 2, 1945 memorandum \"Report on Surrender of Dachau Concentration Camp</ref> He proceeded to take control of the camp in some tumult; thereafter, he toured the camp with a group of reporters<ref>Kerstin Schwenke, ''Die Besatzer und die \u00d6ffnung der Konzentrationslager in Bayern am Beispiel des Lagers Dachau'', (2008), p.11</ref> (including [[Marguerite Higgins]]).<ref>{{cite book|author=Sam Dunn|title=Dachau 29 April 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BDiIVWgm3bUC&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=57|publisher=Texas Tech University Press|year=1998|accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> A description of the surrender appears in Gen. Henning Linden's memorandum to Maj. Gen. [[Harry J. Collins]], entitled \"Report on Surrender of Dachau Concentration Camp\":\n\n{{quotation|As we approached the southwest corner, three people came forward with a flag of truce. We met them about 75 yards north of the southwest corner. These three people were a Swiss [[International Committee of the Red Cross|Red Cross]] representative, Victor Maurer, and two SS troopers who said they were the camp commander and his assistant. They had come here on the night of the 28th to take over from the regular camp personnel for the purpose of surrendering the camp to the advancing Americans. The Swiss Red Cross representative said there were about 100 SS guards in the camp who had their arms stacked except for the people in the tower.... He had given instructions that there would be no shots fired and it would take about 50 men to relieve the guards, as there were 42,000 \"half-crazed\" inmates, many of them [[typhus]] infected... He asked if I were an officer. I replied, \"I am Assistant Division Commander of the 42nd Infantry Division and will accept the surrender of the camp in the name of the Rainbow Division for the United States Army....\"<ref>Sam Dann, ''Dachau 29 April 1945: The Rainbow Liberation Memoirs'', p.14-15</ref>}}\n\n==Capture communiqu\u00e9==\nGen. of the Army [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] issued a communiqu\u00e9 regarding the capture of Dachau concentration camp: \"Our forces liberated and mopped up the infamous concentration camp at Dachau. Approximately 32,000 [[Holocaust survivors|prisoners were liberated]]; 300 SS camp guards were quickly neutralized.\"<ref>Staff, quoting Abram Sachar on [http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/camps/dachau/dachau-01.html The Liberation of Dachau], [[Nizkor Project]].</ref>\n\nMilitary historian Earl Ziemke describes the event:\n\n{{quotation|The Americans came on April 29, a Sunday. Work had stopped in the camp on Wednesday, and an evacuation was being organized. One transport of 4,000 prisoners was able to get away, but the 42nd and 45th Infantry Divisions covered the 40 miles from the [[Danube River|Danube]] faster than the Germans expected. At noon on Sunday the camp was quiet, and the SS guards were at their posts in the towers when the cry \"Americans!\" went up. A prisoner rushed toward the gate, and a guard shot him. Outside, a single American soldier stood looking casually at the towers while the guards eyed him and others who were two or three hundred yards way. When the Americans opened fire, the guards in the gate tower came down, hands in the air. One held a pistol behind his back, and the first American shot him. In the next few minutes a jeep drove up; in it were a blonde female [[war correspondent]] and a [[chaplain]]. The chaplain asked the prisoners, now crowding to the gate, to join him in the [[Lord's Prayer]]. ...Troops of the 42nd and 45th Divisions who liberated Dachau in the afternoon on 29 April were fighting in [[Munich]] the next morning and by nightfall had, along with XV Corps' other three divisions, captured the city that was the capital of Bavaria and the birthplace of Nazism.|Earl F. Ziemke<ref>Earl F. Ziemke, ''The U.S. Army in the occupation of Germany 1944\u20131946'', Center of Military History, United States Army, Washington, D. C., 1990, Library of Congress Catalog Card Number 75-619027 [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/other/us-army_germany_1944-46_ch14.htm Chapter XIV: Eclipse] pp. 252,253.</ref>}}\n\n==Killings by U.S. soldiers==\n[[File:Dachau execution coalyard 1945-04-29.jpg|thumb|Photo allegedly showing execution of SS troops in a coal yard in the area of the Dachau concentration camp during its liberation. April 29, 1945 ([[U.S. Army]] photograph)<ref group=\"Note\">The caption for the photograph in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|U.S. National Archives]] reads, \"SC208765, Soldiers of the 42nd Infantry Division, U.S. Seventh Army, order SS men to come forward when one of their number tried to escape from the Dachau, Germany, concentration camp after it was captured by U.S. forces.  Men on the ground in background feign death by falling as the guards fired a volley at the fleeing SS men. (157th Regt. 4/29/45).\"</ref> ]]\n<!--NOTE...Before changing anything about the image-caption above, please join the discussion about the caption on this article's talkpage so a consensus can be reached as to its length and text.-->\n[[File:Dachau watchtower b 1945-04.jpg|thumb|Dead SS Guards lying at the foot of KZ Dachau Watchtower \"B\"]]\n[[File:Killed SS Cammo Dachau.jpg|thumb|Closeup of the bodies of SS personnel lying at the base of the tower from which U.S. soldiers had initially come under attack by a German machine gun.]]\n\n===Sparks account===\nLt. Col. [[Felix L. Sparks]], a battalion commander of the 157th Infantry Regiment, 45th Infantry Division, Seventh United States Army, wrote about the incident. Sparks watched as about 50 German prisoners captured by the 157th Infantry Regiment were confined in an area that had been used for storing coal. The area was partially enclosed by an L-shaped masonry wall about {{convert|8|ft|m|abbr=on}} high and next to a hospital. The German POWs were watched over by a machine gun team from Company I. He left those men behind to head towards the center of the camp where there were SS who had not yet surrendered; he had only gone a short distance when he heard a soldier yell, \"They're trying to get away!\" and then machine-gun fire coming from the area he had just left. He ran back and kicked a 19-year-old soldier nicknamed \"Birdeye\" who was manning the machine gun and who had killed about 12 of the prisoners and wounded several more.<ref name=humanities-international>{{cite news |title=DACHAU CONCENTRATION CAMP \u2013 LIBERATION |url=http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation |date=2002 |accessdate=December 20, 2013 |first=R.H. |last=Perez |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010045411/http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation/ |archivedate=October 10, 2013 }}</ref> The gunner, who was crying hysterically, said that the prisoners had tried to escape. Sparks said that he doubted the story; Sparks placed an [[Non-commissioned officer|NCO]] on the gun before resuming his journey towards the center of the camp.<ref name=AP>Albert Panebianco (ed). [http://www.45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm Dachau its liberation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928231321/http://www.45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm |date=September 28, 2011 }} 157th Infantry Association, Felix L. Sparks, Secretary June 15, 1989. ([http://www.remember.org/witness/sparks2.html backup site])</ref> Sparks further stated:\n\n{{quotation|It was the foregoing incident which has given rise to wild claims in various publications that most or all of the German prisoners captured at Dachau were executed. Nothing could be further from the truth. The total number of German guards killed at Dachau during that day most certainly did not exceed fifty, with thirty probably being a more accurate figure. The regimental records for that date indicate that over a thousand German prisoners were brought to the regimental collecting point. Since my task force was leading the regimental attack, almost all the prisoners were taken by the task force, including several hundred from Dachau.|Felix L. Sparks<ref name=AP/>}}\n\n===Buechner account===\nIn the U.S. military \"Investigation of Alleged Mistreatment of German Guards at Dachau\" conducted by Lt. Col. Joseph Whitaker, the account given by Howard Buechner (then a first lieutenant in the United States Army and medical officer with the 3rd Battalion of the 157th Infantry), to Whitaker on May 5, 1945 did not contradict the Sparks account. Buechner's sworn testimony was that around 16:00 he arrived in the yard where the German soldiers had been shot, and that he \"saw 15 or 16 dead and wounded German soldiers lying along the wall\". He noted that some of the wounded soldiers were still moving, but he did not examine any of them. He answered \"Yes, sir\" when asked if he was the surgeon of the 3rd Battalion, 157th Infantry, at that time, and did not know if any medical attention was called for the wounded.<ref name=\"abraham.cs.uml.edu\">\"...investigation of alleged mistreatment of German guards at the Concentration Camp at Dachau, Germany...\"  {{cite web |url=http://abraham.cs.uml.edu/secretwar/GlobeSecretHistory/index5_transcript_46.shtml |title= Globe Secret History Index No.5 |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918030939/http://abraham.cs.uml.edu/secretwar/GlobeSecretHistory/index5_transcript_46.shtml |archivedate=September 18, 2013 }} Retrieved June 11, 2014</ref><ref name=Humanitas>{{cite web |url=http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation/ |title=Dachau Concentration Camp Liberation (A Documentary) |author=R.H. Perez |publisher=Humanitas International |year=2002 |accessdate=January 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324034016/http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation/ |archivedate=March 24, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Buechner's 1986 book, ''Dachau: The Hour of the Avenger: An Eyewitness Account'',<ref name=Buechner>{{Cite book|last=Buechner|first=Howard|title=Dachau: The Hour of the Avenger: An Eyewitness Account|page=97|publisher=Metairie, Thunderdbird Press, Inc.|date=June 1986|isbn= 0-913159-04-2}}</ref> U.S. forces killed 520 German soldiers, including 346 killed on the orders of 1st Lt. Jack Bushyhead, in an alleged mass execution in the coalyard several hours after the first hospital shooting. Buechner did not witness the alleged incident, and his sworn testimony was that he \"saw 15 or 16 dead and wounded German soldiers lying along the wall.\"  His sworn testimony in the official investigation report also did not include any mention of a second shooting.<ref name=\"abraham.cs.uml.edu\"/><ref name=Humanitas/> David L. Israel disputed this account in his book ''The Day the Thunderbird Cried'':\n\n{{quotation|Buechner's inaccuracies and arbitrary use of figures in citing the untrue story about the total liquidation of all SS troops found in Dachau was eagerly accepted by Revisionist organizations and exploited to meet their own distorted stories of Dachau.|David L. Israel<ref name =Israel>{{Cite book|last=Israel|first=David L.|title=The Day the Thunderbird Cried: Untold Stories of World War II|publisher=Emek Press|date=September 30, 2005|isbn=0-9770591-0-3|page=176}}</ref>}}\n\nJ\u00fcrgen Zarusky also concluded that Buechner's claims were incorrect.<ref>{{Cite book |last= Zarusky |first= J\u00fcrgen |chapter= 'That is not the American Way of Fighting:' The Shooting of Captured SS-Men During the Liberation of Dachau |editor1= Wolfgang Benz |editor2= Barbara Distel |title= Dachau and the Nazi Terror 1933\u20131945 |volume= 2, Studies and Reports |publisher= Verlag Dachauer Hefte |location= Dachau |year= 2002 |page= [https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/156 156] |isbn= 978-3-9808587-1-7 |url= https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/156 }} [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/faculty/marcuse/dachau/archive/ZaruskyDachauLiberationMassacre2002excerpt.pdf Excerpt online]</ref>\n\n===Other accounts===\nAbram Sachar reported, \"Some of the Nazis were rounded up and summarily executed along with the guard dogs.\"<ref>Staff, quoting Abram Sachar on [http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/camps/dachau/dachau-01.html The Liberation of Dachau], [[Nizkor Project]]. citing Sachar, Abram L. The Redemption of the Unwanted. New York: St. Martin's/Marek, 1983</ref>\n\nAccording to J\u00fcrgen Zarusky (originally published in a 1997 article in ''Dachauer Hefte''), 16 SS men were shot in the coalyard (one more killed by a camp inmate), 17 in Tower B, and perhaps a few more killed by U.S. soldiers in the incident. Anywhere from a few to 25 or 50 more were killed by inmates. Zarusky's research makes use of the detailed interrogation records contained in Whitaker's official May 1945 investigation report, which became accessible in 1992, as well as a collection of documents compiled by General Henning Linden's son.<ref>{{Cite book |last= Zarusky |first= J\u00fcrgen |chapter= 'That is not the American Way of Fighting:' The Shooting of Captured SS-Men During the Liberation of Dachau |editor1= Wolfgang Benz |editor2= Barbara Distel |title= Dachau and the Nazi Terror 1933\u20131945 |volume= 2, Studies and Reports |publisher= Verlag Dachauer Hefte |location= Dachau |year= 2002 |pages= [https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/133 133\u2013160] |isbn= 978-3-9808587-1-7 |url= https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/133 }} [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/faculty/marcuse/dachau/archive/ZaruskyDachauLiberationMassacre2002excerpt.pdf Excerpt online]</ref>\n\nThe Dachau liberation reprisals were documented among others by U.S. Army photographers [[Paul Richard Averitt|Paul Averitt]], [[George Gaberlavage]], [[Sidney Rachlin]] and [[Ed Royce, Sr.]]\n\n==Killings by the inmates==\nWalenty Lenarczyk, a prisoner at Dachau, stated that following the camp's liberation \"prisoners swarmed over the wire and grabbed the Americans and lifted them to their shoulders... other prisoners caught the SS men... The first SS man elbowed one or two prisoners out of his way, but the courage of the prisoners mounted, they knocked them down and nobody could see whether they were stomped or what, but they were killed.\"<ref name=AP/> Elsewhere in the camp SS men, Kapos and informers were beaten badly with fists, sticks and shovels. There was at least one incident where US soldiers turned away from two prisoners beating a German guard to death with a shovel, and Lt. Bill Walsh witnessed one such beating.<ref>The Liberator : One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. pages 282, 283, 290</ref> Another soldier witnessed an inmate stomping on an SS trooper's face until \"there wasn't much left.\" When the soldier said to him, \"You've got a lot of hate in your heart,\" he simply nodded.<ref>Cpl. Robert W. Flora, H Company, 22d Regiment Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 77.</ref>\n\nAn American chaplain was told by three young Jewish men, who had left the camp during liberation, that they had beaten to death one of the more sadistic SS guards when they discovered him hiding in a barn and dressed as a peasant.<ref>Rabbi Eli A. Bohnen, Chaplain Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 159.</ref>\n\n==United States Army investigation==\nLt. Col. Joseph Whitaker, the Seventh Army's Assistant Inspector General, was ordered to investigate after witnesses came forward testifying about the killings. He issued a report on June 8, 1945, called the \"Investigation of Alleged Mistreatment of German Guards at Dachau\" and also known as \"the I.G. Report\". In 1991, an archived copy was found in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]] in Washington, D.C., and was made public.<ref name=Humanitas/>\n\nWhitaker reported that close to the back entrance to the camp Lt. William P. Walsh, commander of Company \"I\", 157th Infantry, shot four German soldiers in a [[box car]] who had surrendered to him. Pvt. Albert C. Pruitt then climbed into the box car and performed a ''[[coup de gr\u00e2ce]]'' on the wounded men.<ref name=Humanitas/>\n\nAfter he had entered the camp, Walsh, along with Lt. Jack Bushyhead, the executive officer of Company \"I\", organized the segregation of POWs into those who were members of the Wehrmacht and those who were in the SS. The SS were marched into a separate enclosure and were shot by members of \"I\" Company with several different types of weapons.<ref name=Humanitas/>\n\nThe investigation resulted in the U.S. military considering [[court-martial|courts-martial]] against those involved, including the battalion commander [[Felix L. Sparks|Lt. Col. Felix Sparks]], while Lt. Howard Buechner was cited in the report for dereliction of duty for not giving the wounded SS men in the coal yard medical aid.<ref name=Humanitas/> However, [[General (United States)|Gen.]] [[George S. Patton]], the recently appointed military governor of Bavaria, chose to dismiss the charges. Therefore, the witnesses to the killings were never cross-examined in court.<ref name=AP/>\n\nCol. Charles L. Decker, an acting deputy judge advocate, concluded in late 1945 that, while there had probably been a violation of international law, \"in the light of the conditions which greeted the eyes of the first combat troops, it is not believed that justice or equity demand that the difficult and perhaps impossible task of fixing individual responsibility now be undertaken\".<ref>The Liberator: One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. page 320</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Germany]]\n* [[Allied war crimes during World War II]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n{{refbegin}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Complete transcript of the US Army investigation [https://web.archive.org/web/20141103034054/http://abraham.cs.uml.edu/secretwar/GlobeSecretHistory/index5_transcript.shtml Boston.com | Boston Globe Online | Nation | The Secret History of World War II]\n* Goodell, Stephen, Kevin A Mahoney; Sybil Milton (1995). \"1945: The Year of Liberation\". Washington, D.C., U.S.: U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum. {{ISBN|0-89604-700-8}}\n* Marcuse, Harold (2001). \"Legacies of Dachau : The Uses and Abuses of a Concentration Camp, 1933\u20132001\". Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-55204-4}}\n* Zarusky, J\u00fcrgen, \"'That is not the American Way of Fighting:' The Shooting of Captured SS-Men During the Liberation of Dachau,\" in: [[Wolfgang Benz]], Barbara Distel (eds.): ''Dachau and the Nazi Terror 1933\u20131945'', vol. 2, Studies and Reports (Dachau 2002), pp.&nbsp;133\u2013160. (German original in ''Dachauer Hefte'' vol. 13, 1997).\n\n{{Coord|48|16|13|N|11|28|05|E|region:DE-BY_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dachau Liberation Reprisals}}\n[[Category:1945 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Dachau concentration camp]]\n[[Category:Extrajudicial killings in World War II]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1945]]\n[[Category:Massacres committed by the United States]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Germany]]\n[[Category:Military history of the United States during World War II]]\n[[Category:Murder in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war massacres by the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Reprisals against Germans during the liberation of Dachau}}\nDuring the '''Dachau liberation reprisals''', German prisoners of war were killed by U.S. soldiers and concentration camp internees at the [[Dachau concentration camp]] on April 29, 1945, during [[World War II]]. It is unclear how many [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] members were killed in the incident but most estimates place the number killed at around 35\u201350.  In the days before the camp's liberation, SS guards at the camp had  forced 7,000 inmates on a [[Death marches (Holocaust)|death march]] that resulted in the death of many from exposure and shooting.<ref name=\"USHM --- death marches\">{{cite web|title=Death Marches|url=https://www.ushmm.org/outreach/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007734|website=www.ushmm.org|publisher=U.S. Holocaust Museum|accessdate=March 4, 2018|language=en}}</ref> When Allied soldiers [[Dachau concentration camp#Liberation|liberated Dachau]], they were variously shocked, horrified, disturbed, and angered at finding the massed corpses of internees, and by the combativeness of some of the remaining guards who allegedly fired on them.\n\n==Discoveries==\n[[File:Dead corpses in train dachau.jpg|thumb|Corpses of internees who were left by their Nazi guards to die in a train at Dachau. Thousands of prisoners were murdered by the Nazis in the days before the camp's liberation.]]\n[[File:Kz dachau liberation person.jpg|thumb|SS men confer with General [[Henning Linden]] during the capture of the Dachau concentration camp. Pictured from left to right: SS aide, camp leader Untersturmf\u00fchrer Heinrich Wicker (mostly hidden by the aide), [[Paul M. G. L\u00e9vy]], a Belgian journalist (man with helmet looking to his left), Dr. Victor Maurer (back), Gen. Henning Linden (man with helmet, looking to his right) and some U.S. soldiers.]]\n\nOn April 29, 1945, soldiers of the 3rd Battalion, 157th Infantry Regiment, 45th Infantry Division, commanded by Lieutenant Colonel [[Felix L. Sparks]], approaching the sprawling Dachau complex from the southwest, found 39 railway [[boxcar]]s containing some 2,000 skeletal corpses parked on rail tracks just outside the complex itself. Brain tissue was splattered on the ground from one victim found nearby with a crushed skull. The smell of decaying bodies and human excrement, and the sight of naked, emaciated bodies induced vomiting, crying, disbelief, and rage in the advancing troops.<ref name=\"US Holocaust Museum \u2013 Dachau\">{{Cite web|url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/dachau|title=Dachau|website=encyclopedia.ushmm.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Dachau, May Day, 1945\">[http://www.evesmag.com/dachau.htm \"Dachau, May Day, 1945\"], Eve's Magazine</ref><ref name=\"The Liberator 2012. page 273, 274\">The Liberator : One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. page 273, 274</ref> Advancing soldiers from H Company, 22nd Regiment used a loudspeaker to call on the SS to surrender, but they continued to fire in bursts.<ref>Corporal Robert W. Flora, H Company, 22d Regiment Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 76.</ref><ref>Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 101</ref>\n\nUpon moving deeper into the complex, and the prisoner area itself, the soldiers found more bodies. Some had been dead for hours and days before the camp's capture and lay where they had died. Soldiers reported seeing a row of concrete structures that contained rooms full of hundreds of naked and barely clothed dead bodies piled floor to ceiling, a coal-fired crematorium, and a gas chamber.<ref name=\"Dachau and Its Liberation, by Felix L. Sparks\">{{Cite web|url=http://45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm|title=Dachau|website=45thinfantrydivision.com|access-date=April 1, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217085000/http://www.45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm|archive-date=February 17, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> \"The stench of death was overpowering,\" Sparks recalled.<ref>The Liberator : One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. pages 281, 282</ref>\n\n==Surrender==\nAccording to [[Harold Marcuse]], an American professor of German history, the camp commander SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer [[Martin Gottfried Weiss|Martin Weiss]], together with the camp guards and the SS garrisons, had fled the camp before the arrival of U.S. troops. SS-[[Untersturmf\u00fchrer]] Heinrich Wicker (killed after the surrender) was left in charge and had roughly 560 personnel at his disposal; these came from conscripted inmates of the SS disciplinary prison inside the Dachau concentration camp and Hungarian [[Waffen-SS]] troops.<ref>Harold Marcuse, ''Legacies of Dachau: The uses and abuses of a concentration camp'', 1933\u20132001, p.52</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 1945 Dachau was surrendered to [[Brig. Gen.]] [[Henning Linden]] of the [[42nd Infantry Division (United States)|42nd Infantry Division]] of the U.S. Army by Untersturmf\u00fchrer Wicker. According to Linden, he arrived at the command post in Dachau at about 15:00 and proceeded to make his way across the Amper River to the site of the complex approximately one-half kilometer south of the bridge he crossed.<ref>Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. p 14. Text from May 2, 1945 memorandum \"Report on Surrender of Dachau Concentration Camp</ref> He proceeded to take control of the camp in some tumult; thereafter, he toured the camp with a group of reporters<ref>Kerstin Schwenke, ''Die Besatzer und die \u00d6ffnung der Konzentrationslager in Bayern am Beispiel des Lagers Dachau'', (2008), p.11</ref> (including [[Marguerite Higgins]]).<ref>{{cite book|author=Sam Dunn|title=Dachau 29 April 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BDiIVWgm3bUC&pg=PA57#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=57|publisher=Texas Tech University Press|year=1998|accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> A description of the surrender appears in Gen. Henning Linden's memorandum to Maj. Gen. [[Harry J. Collins]], entitled \"Report on Surrender of Dachau Concentration Camp\":\n\n{{quotation|As we approached the southwest corner, three people came forward with a flag of truce. We met them about 75 yards north of the southwest corner. These three people were a Swiss [[International Committee of the Red Cross|Red Cross]] representative, Victor Maurer, and two SS troopers who said they were the camp commander and his assistant. They had come here on the night of the 28th to take over from the regular camp personnel for the purpose of surrendering the camp to the advancing Americans. The Swiss Red Cross representative said there were about 100 SS guards in the camp who had their arms stacked except for the people in the tower.... He had given instructions that there would be no shots fired and it would take about 50 men to relieve the guards, as there were 42,000 \"half-crazed\" inmates, many of them [[typhus]] infected... He asked if I were an officer. I replied, \"I am Assistant Division Commander of the 42nd Infantry Division and will accept the surrender of the camp in the name of the Rainbow Division for the United States Army....\"<ref>Sam Dann, ''Dachau 29 April 1945: The Rainbow Liberation Memoirs'', p.14-15</ref>}}\n\n==Capture communiqu\u00e9==\nGen. of the Army [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] issued a communiqu\u00e9 regarding the capture of Dachau concentration camp: \"Our forces liberated and mopped up the infamous concentration camp at Dachau. Approximately 32,000 [[Holocaust survivors|prisoners were liberated]]; 300 SS camp guards were quickly neutralized.\"<ref>Staff, quoting Abram Sachar on [http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/camps/dachau/dachau-01.html The Liberation of Dachau], [[Nizkor Project]].</ref>\n\nMilitary historian Earl Ziemke describes the event:\n\n{{quotation|The Americans came on April 29, a Sunday. Work had stopped in the camp on Wednesday, and an evacuation was being organized. One transport of 4,000 prisoners was able to get away, but the 42nd and 45th Infantry Divisions covered the 40 miles from the [[Danube River|Danube]] faster than the Germans expected. At noon on Sunday the camp was quiet, and the SS guards were at their posts in the towers when the cry \"Americans!\" went up. A prisoner rushed toward the gate, and a guard shot him. Outside, a single American soldier stood looking casually at the towers while the guards eyed him and others who were two or three hundred yards way. When the Americans opened fire, the guards in the gate tower came down, hands in the air. One held a pistol behind his back, and the first American shot him. In the next few minutes a jeep drove up; in it were a blonde female [[war correspondent]] and a [[chaplain]]. The chaplain asked the prisoners, now crowding to the gate, to join him in the [[Lord's Prayer]]. ...Troops of the 42nd and 45th Divisions who liberated Dachau in the afternoon on 29 April were fighting in [[Munich]] the next morning and by nightfall had, along with XV Corps' other three divisions, captured the city that was the capital of Bavaria and the birthplace of Nazism.|Earl F. Ziemke<ref>Earl F. Ziemke, ''The U.S. Army in the occupation of Germany 1944\u20131946'', Center of Military History, United States Army, Washington, D. C., 1990, Library of Congress Catalog Card Number 75-619027 [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/other/us-army_germany_1944-46_ch14.htm Chapter XIV: Eclipse] pp. 252,253.</ref>}}\n\n==Killings by U.S. soldiers==\n[[File:Dachau execution coalyard 1945-04-29.jpg|thumb|Photo allegedly showing execution of SS troops in a coal yard in the area of the Dachau concentration camp during its liberation. April 29, 1945 ([[U.S. Army]] photograph)<ref group=\"Note\">The caption for the photograph in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|U.S. National Archives]] reads, \"SC208765, Soldiers of the 42nd Infantry Division, U.S. Seventh Army, order SS men to come forward when one of their number tried to escape from the Dachau, Germany, concentration camp after it was captured by U.S. forces.  Men on the ground in background feign death by falling as the guards fired a volley at the fleeing SS men. (157th Regt. 4/29/45).\"</ref> ]]\n<!--NOTE...Before changing anything about the image-caption above, please join the discussion about the caption on this article's talkpage so a consensus can be reached as to its length and text.-->\n[[File:Dachau watchtower b 1945-04.jpg|thumb|Dead SS Guards lying at the foot of KZ Dachau Watchtower \"B\"]]\n[[File:Killed SS Cammo Dachau.jpg|thumb|Closeup of the bodies of SS personnel lying at the base of the tower from which U.S. soldiers had initially come under attack by a German machine gun.]]\n\n===Sparks account===\nLt. Col. [[Felix L. Sparks]], a battalion commander of the 157th Infantry Regiment, 45th Infantry Division, Seventh United States Army, wrote about the incident. Sparks watched as about 50 German prisoners captured by the 157th Infantry Regiment were confined in an area that had been used for storing coal. The area was partially enclosed by an L-shaped masonry wall about {{convert|8|ft|m|abbr=on}} high and next to a hospital. The German POWs were watched over by a machine gun team from Company I. He left those men behind to head towards the center of the camp where there were SS who had not yet surrendered; he had only gone a short distance when he heard a soldier yell, \"They're trying to get away!\" and then machine-gun fire coming from the area he had just left. He ran back and kicked a 19-year-old soldier nicknamed \"Birdeye\" who was manning the machine gun and who had killed about 12 of the prisoners and wounded several more.<ref name=humanities-international>{{cite news |title=DACHAU CONCENTRATION CAMP \u2013 LIBERATION |url=http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation |date=2002 |accessdate=December 20, 2013 |first=R.H. |last=Perez |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010045411/http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation/ |archivedate=October 10, 2013 }}</ref> The gunner, who was crying hysterically, said that the prisoners had tried to escape. Sparks said that he doubted the story; Sparks placed an [[Non-commissioned officer|NCO]] on the gun before resuming his journey towards the center of the camp.<ref name=AP>Albert Panebianco (ed). [http://www.45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm Dachau its liberation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928231321/http://www.45thinfantrydivision.com/index14.htm |date=September 28, 2011 }} 157th Infantry Association, Felix L. Sparks, Secretary June 15, 1989. ([http://www.remember.org/witness/sparks2.html backup site])</ref> Sparks further stated:\n\n{{quotation|It was the foregoing incident which has given rise to wild claims in various publications that most or all of the German prisoners captured at Dachau were executed. Nothing could be further from the truth. The total number of German guards killed at Dachau during that day most certainly did not exceed fifty, with thirty probably being a more accurate figure. The regimental records for that date indicate that over a thousand German prisoners were brought to the regimental collecting point. Since my task force was leading the regimental attack, almost all the prisoners were taken by the task force, including several hundred from Dachau.|Felix L. Sparks<ref name=AP/>}}\n\n===Buechner account===\nIn the U.S. military \"Investigation of Alleged Mistreatment of German Guards at Dachau\" conducted by Lt. Col. Joseph Whitaker, the account given by Howard Buechner (then a first lieutenant in the United States Army and medical officer with the 3rd Battalion of the 157th Infantry), to Whitaker on May 5, 1945 did not contradict the Sparks account. Buechner's sworn testimony was that around 16:00 he arrived in the yard where the German soldiers had been shot, and that he \"saw 15 or 16 dead and wounded German soldiers lying along the wall\". He noted that some of the wounded soldiers were still moving, but he did not examine any of them. He answered \"Yes, sir\" when asked if he was the surgeon of the 3rd Battalion, 157th Infantry, at that time, and did not know if any medical attention was called for the wounded.<ref name=\"abraham.cs.uml.edu\">\"...investigation of alleged mistreatment of German guards at the Concentration Camp at Dachau, Germany...\"  {{cite web |url=http://abraham.cs.uml.edu/secretwar/GlobeSecretHistory/index5_transcript_46.shtml |title= Globe Secret History Index No.5 |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918030939/http://abraham.cs.uml.edu/secretwar/GlobeSecretHistory/index5_transcript_46.shtml |archivedate=September 18, 2013 }} Retrieved June 11, 2014</ref><ref name=Humanitas>{{cite web |url=http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation/ |title=Dachau Concentration Camp Liberation (A Documentary) |author=R.H. Perez |publisher=Humanitas International |year=2002 |accessdate=January 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324034016/http://www.humanitas-international.org/archive/dachau-liberation/ |archivedate=March 24, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Buechner's 1986 book, ''Dachau: The Hour of the Avenger: An Eyewitness Account'',<ref name=Buechner>{{Cite book|last=Buechner|first=Howard|title=Dachau: The Hour of the Avenger: An Eyewitness Account|page=97|publisher=Metairie, Thunderdbird Press, Inc.|date=June 1986|isbn= 0-913159-04-2}}</ref> U.S. forces killed 520 German soldiers, including 346 killed on the orders of 1st Lt. Jack Bushyhead, in an alleged mass execution in the coalyard several hours after the first hospital shooting. Buechner did not witness the alleged incident, and his sworn testimony was that he \"saw 15 or 16 dead and wounded German soldiers lying along the wall.\"  His sworn testimony in the official investigation report also did not include any mention of a second shooting.<ref name=\"abraham.cs.uml.edu\"/><ref name=Humanitas/> David L. Israel disputed this account in his book ''The Day the Thunderbird Cried'':\n\n{{quotation|Buechner's inaccuracies and arbitrary use of figures in citing the untrue story about the total liquidation of all SS troops found in Dachau was eagerly accepted by Revisionist organizations and exploited to meet their own distorted stories of Dachau.|David L. Israel<ref name =Israel>{{Cite book|last=Israel|first=David L.|title=The Day the Thunderbird Cried: Untold Stories of World War II|publisher=Emek Press|date=September 30, 2005|isbn=0-9770591-0-3|page=176}}</ref>}}\n\nJ\u00fcrgen Zarusky also concluded that Buechner's claims were incorrect.<ref>{{Cite book |last= Zarusky |first= J\u00fcrgen |chapter= 'That is not the American Way of Fighting:' The Shooting of Captured SS-Men During the Liberation of Dachau |editor1= Wolfgang Benz |editor2= Barbara Distel |title= Dachau and the Nazi Terror 1933\u20131945 |volume= 2, Studies and Reports |publisher= Verlag Dachauer Hefte |location= Dachau |year= 2002 |page= [https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/156 156] |isbn= 978-3-9808587-1-7 |url= https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/156 }} [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/faculty/marcuse/dachau/archive/ZaruskyDachauLiberationMassacre2002excerpt.pdf Excerpt online]</ref>\n\n===Other accounts===\nAbram Sachar reported, \"Some of the Nazis were rounded up and summarily executed along with the guard dogs.\"<ref>Staff, quoting Abram Sachar on [http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/camps/dachau/dachau-01.html The Liberation of Dachau], [[Nizkor Project]]. citing Sachar, Abram L. The Redemption of the Unwanted. New York: St. Martin's/Marek, 1983</ref>\n\nAccording to J\u00fcrgen Zarusky (originally published in a 1997 article in ''Dachauer Hefte''), 16 SS men were shot in the coalyard (one more killed by a camp inmate), 17 in Tower B, and perhaps a few more killed by U.S. soldiers in the incident. Anywhere from a few to 25 or 50 more were killed by inmates. Zarusky's research makes use of the detailed interrogation records contained in Whitaker's official May 1945 investigation report, which became accessible in 1992, as well as a collection of documents compiled by General Henning Linden's son.<ref>{{Cite book |last= Zarusky |first= J\u00fcrgen |chapter= 'That is not the American Way of Fighting:' The Shooting of Captured SS-Men During the Liberation of Dachau |editor1= Wolfgang Benz |editor2= Barbara Distel |title= Dachau and the Nazi Terror 1933\u20131945 |volume= 2, Studies and Reports |publisher= Verlag Dachauer Hefte |location= Dachau |year= 2002 |pages= [https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/133 133\u2013160] |isbn= 978-3-9808587-1-7 |url= https://archive.org/details/dachaunaziterror0000unse/page/133 }} [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/faculty/marcuse/dachau/archive/ZaruskyDachauLiberationMassacre2002excerpt.pdf Excerpt online]</ref>\n\nThe Dachau liberation reprisals were documented among others by U.S. Army photographers [[Paul Richard Averitt|Paul Averitt]], [[George Gaberlavage]], [[Sidney Rachlin]] and [[Ed Royce, Sr.]]\n\n==Killings by the inmates==\nWalenty Lenarczyk, a prisoner at Dachau, stated that following the camp's liberation \"prisoners swarmed over the wire and grabbed the Americans and lifted them to their shoulders... other prisoners caught the SS men... The first SS man elbowed one or two prisoners out of his way, but the courage of the prisoners mounted, they knocked them down and nobody could see whether they were stomped or what, but they were killed.\"<ref name=AP/> Elsewhere in the camp SS men, Kapos and informers were beaten badly with fists, sticks and shovels. There was at least one incident where US soldiers turned away from two prisoners beating a German guard to death with a shovel, and Lt. Bill Walsh witnessed one such beating.<ref>The Liberator : One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. pages 282, 283, 290</ref> Another soldier witnessed an inmate stomping on an SS trooper's face until \"there wasn't much left.\" When the soldier said to him, \"You've got a lot of hate in your heart,\" he simply nodded.<ref>Cpl. Robert W. Flora, H Company, 22d Regiment Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 77.</ref>\n\nAn American chaplain was told by three young Jewish men, who had left the camp during liberation, that they had beaten to death one of the more sadistic SS guards when they discovered him hiding in a barn and dressed as a peasant.<ref>Rabbi Eli A. Bohnen, Chaplain Dachau April 29, 1945: the Rainbow liberation memoirs. 1998. Texas Tech University Press. page 159.</ref>\n\n==United States Army investigation==\nLt. Col. Joseph Whitaker, the Seventh Army's Assistant Inspector General, was ordered to investigate after witnesses came forward testifying about the killings. He issued a report on June 8, 1945, called the \"Investigation of Alleged Mistreatment of German Guards at Dachau\" and also known as \"the I.G. Report\". In 1991, an archived copy was found in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]] in Washington, D.C. and was made public.<ref name=Humanitas/>\n\nWhitaker reported that close to the back entrance to the camp Lt. William P. Walsh, commander of Company \"I\", 157th Infantry, shot four German soldiers in a [[box car]] who had surrendered to him. Pvt. Albert C. Pruitt then climbed into the box car and performed a ''[[coup de gr\u00e2ce]]'' on the wounded men.<ref name=Humanitas/>\n\nAfter he had entered the camp, Walsh, along with Lt. Jack Bushyhead, the executive officer of Company \"I\", organized the segregation of POWs into those who were members of the Wehrmacht and those who were in the SS. The SS were marched into a separate enclosure and were shot by members of \"I\" Company with several different types of weapons.<ref name=Humanitas/>\n\nThe investigation resulted in the U.S. military considering [[court-martial|courts-martial]] against those involved, including the battalion commander [[Felix L. Sparks|Lt. Col. Felix Sparks]], while Lt. Howard Buechner was cited in the report for dereliction of duty for not giving the wounded SS men in the coal yard medical aid.<ref name=Humanitas/> However, [[General (United States)|Gen.]] [[George S. Patton]], the recently appointed military governor of Bavaria, chose to dismiss the charges. Therefore, the witnesses to the killings were never cross-examined in court.<ref name=AP/>\n\nCol. Charles L. Decker, an acting deputy judge advocate, concluded in late 1945 that, while there had probably been a violation of international law, \"in the light of the conditions which greeted the eyes of the first combat troops, it is not believed that justice or equity demand that the difficult and perhaps impossible task of fixing individual responsibility now be undertaken\".<ref>The Liberator: One World War II Soldier's 500-Day Odyssey from the Beaches of Sicily to the Gates of Dachau. Alex Kershaw. 2012. Crown. New York. page 320</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Germany]]\n* [[Allied war crimes during World War II]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n{{refbegin}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Complete transcript of the US Army investigation [https://web.archive.org/web/20141103034054/http://abraham.cs.uml.edu/secretwar/GlobeSecretHistory/index5_transcript.shtml Boston.com | Boston Globe Online | Nation | The Secret History of World War II]\n* Goodell, Stephen, Kevin A Mahoney; Sybil Milton (1995). \"1945: The Year of Liberation\". Washington, D.C., U.S.: U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum. {{ISBN|0-89604-700-8}}\n* Marcuse, Harold (2001). \"Legacies of Dachau : The Uses and Abuses of a Concentration Camp, 1933\u20132001\". Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|0-521-55204-4}}\n* Zarusky, J\u00fcrgen, \"'That is not the American Way of Fighting:' The Shooting of Captured SS-Men During the Liberation of Dachau,\" in: [[Wolfgang Benz]], Barbara Distel (eds.): ''Dachau and the Nazi Terror 1933\u20131945'', vol. 2, Studies and Reports (Dachau 2002), pp.&nbsp;133\u2013160. (German original in ''Dachauer Hefte'' vol. 13, 1997).\n\n{{Coord|48|16|13|N|11|28|05|E|region:DE-BY_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dachau Liberation Reprisals}}\n[[Category:1945 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Dachau concentration camp]]\n[[Category:Extrajudicial killings in World War II]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1945]]\n[[Category:Massacres committed by the United States]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Germany]]\n[[Category:Military history of the United States during World War II]]\n[[Category:Murder in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war massacres by the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Cyanolinguophile", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited States Army investigation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dachau_liberation_reprisals"}
{"title_page": "Shacky Tauro", "text_new": "{{short description|Zimbabwean footballer and manager}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Shacky Tauro\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| fullname             = Shackman Tauro\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1959|6|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Rhodesia]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2009|6|17|1959|6|28|df=y}}\n| death_place       = Zimbabwe\n| height               = \n| position             = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| years1               = 1972\u20131991\n| clubs1               = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]]\n| caps1         =  | goals1 =  \n| nationalyears1       = 1980\u20131988\n| nationalteam1        = [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]\n| nationalcaps1 =  | nationalgoals1 =  \n| manageryears1        = 1991\u20131994\n| managerclubs1        = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2        = 1994\u20131996\n| managerclubs2        = [[Blackpool F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Blackpool]]\n| manageryears3        = 1996\u20131997\n| managerclubs3        = [[Arcadia United F.C.|Arcadia United]]\n| manageryears4        = 1997\u20131998\n| managerclubs4        = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]]\n| manageryears5        = 1998\n| managerclubs5        = [[Circle United F.C.|Circle United]]\n| manageryears6        = ????\n| managerclubs6        = [[Zimbabwe women's national football team|Zimbabwe Women]]\n| manageryears7        = 2006\u20132007\n| managerclubs7        = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]]\n| manageryears8        = 2007\u20132009\n| managerclubs8        = [[Shooting Stars F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Shooting Stars]]\n}}\n'''Shackman \"Shacky\" Tauro''' (28 June 1959 \u2013 17 June 2009) was a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[association football|football]] player and coach.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Playing career===\nTauro, who played as a [[forward (association football)|striker]], spent his entire professional career with [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]], and also earned international caps for [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]].\n\nHe was named the [[Zimbabwe Soccer Star of the Year|Rhodesian Soccer Star of the Year]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/zimbpoy.html|title=Zimbabwe \u2013 Player of the Year|publisher=RSSSF}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\nTauro coached [[Blackpool F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Blackpool]], [[Arcadia United F.C.|Arcadia United]], [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]], [[Circle United F.C.|Circle United]], the [[Zimbabwe women's national football team|Zimbabwe women's national team]], and [[Shooting Stars F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Shooting Stars]].\n\n==References==\n\n===General===\n*[http://allafrica.com/stories/200906190010.html Obituary \u2013 All Africa]\n*[http://www.newzimbabwe.com/sports-475-CAPS+United+legend+Tauro+dies/sports.aspx Obituary \u2013 New Zimbabwe]\n\n===Specific===\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tauro, Shacky}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:CAPS United players]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwe international footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean football managers]]\n\n\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n{{Zimbabwe-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Shacky Tauro\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| fullname             = Shackman Tauro\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1959|6|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Rhodesia]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2009|6|17|1959|6|28|df=y}}\n| death_place       = Zimbabwe\n| height               = \n| position             = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| years1               = 1972\u20131991\n| clubs1               = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]]\n| caps1         =  | goals1 =  \n| nationalyears1       = 1980\u20131988\n| nationalteam1        = [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]\n| nationalcaps1 =  | nationalgoals1 =  \n| manageryears1        = 1991\u20131994\n| managerclubs1        = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2        = 1994\u20131996\n| managerclubs2        = [[Blackpool F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Blackpool]]\n| manageryears3        = 1996\u20131997\n| managerclubs3        = [[Arcadia United F.C.|Arcadia United]]\n| manageryears4        = 1997\u20131998\n| managerclubs4        = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]]\n| manageryears5        = 1998\n| managerclubs5        = [[Circle United F.C.|Circle United]]\n| manageryears6        = ????\n| managerclubs6        = [[Zimbabwe women's national football team|Zimbabwe Women]]\n| manageryears7        = 2006\u20132007\n| managerclubs7        = [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]]\n| manageryears8        = 2007\u20132009\n| managerclubs8        = [[Shooting Stars F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Shooting Stars]]\n}}\n'''Shackman \"Shacky\" Tauro''' (28 June 1959 \u2013 17 June 2009) was a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[association football|football]] player and coach.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Playing career===\nTauro, who played as a [[forward (association football)|striker]], spent his entire professional career with [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]], and also earned international caps for [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]].\n\nHe was named the [[Zimbabwe Soccer Star of the Year|Rhodesian Soccer Star of the Year]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/zimbpoy.html|title=Zimbabwe \u2013 Player of the Year|publisher=RSSSF}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching career===\nTauro coached [[Blackpool F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Blackpool]], [[Arcadia United F.C.|Arcadia United]], [[CAPS United F.C.|CAPS United]], [[Circle United F.C.|Circle United]], the [[Zimbabwe women's national football team|Zimbabwe women's national team]], and [[Shooting Stars F.C. (Zimbabwe)|Shooting Stars]].\n\n==References==\n\n===General===\n*[http://allafrica.com/stories/200906190010.html Obituary \u2013 All Africa]\n*[http://www.newzimbabwe.com/sports-475-CAPS+United+legend+Tauro+dies/sports.aspx Obituary \u2013 New Zimbabwe]\n\n===Specific===\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tauro, Shacky}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:CAPS United players]]\n[[Category:Rhodesian footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwe international footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean football managers]]\n\n\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n{{Zimbabwe-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Zimbabwean footballer and manager\", overriding Wikidata description \"Zimbabwean footballer and manager\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shacky_Tauro"}
{"title_page": "Obadiah Tarumbwa", "text_new": "{{short description|Zimbabwean footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Obadiah Tarumbwa\n| fullname            = Obadiah Danger Tarumbwa Moyo\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|11|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bulawayo]], Zimbabwe\n| height              = {{convert|1.93|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position            = [[Attacking midfielder]]\n| currentclub         = [[University of Pretoria F.C.|University of Pretoria]]\n| clubnumber          = \n| youthyears1         = \n| youthclubs1         = \n| years1              = 2000\u20132008\n| years2              = 2008\u20132009\n| years3              = 2009\n| years4              = 2009\u20132011\n| years5              = 2011\u20132012\n| years6              = 2012\u20132013\n| years7              = 2013\n| years8              = 2013\u20132014\n| years9              = 2014\u20132015\n| years10             = 2015\u20132016\n| years11             = 2016\u2013\n| clubs1              = [[Highlanders F.C.|Highlanders]]\n| clubs2              = [[Cercle Brugge K.S.V.|Cercle Brugge]]\n| clubs3              = [[Bantu Rovers]]\n| clubs4              = [[Enosis Neon Paralimni FC|Enosis Neon Paralimni]]\n| clubs5              = [[APOP Kinyras FC|APOP Kinyras]]\n| clubs6              = [[Ermis Aradippou]]\n| clubs7              = [[Sofapaka F.C.|Sofapaka]]\n| clubs8              = [[University of Pretoria F.C.|Tuks]]\n| clubs9              = [[Bantu Tshintsha Guluva Rovers F.C.|Bantu Rovers]]\n| clubs10             = \u2192 [[Highlanders F.C.|Highlanders]] (loan)\n| clubs11             = [[Chicken Inn F.C.|Chicken Inn]]\n| caps1               = 84   | goals1         = 32\n| caps2               = 6    | goals2         = 0\n| caps3               = 5    | goals3         = 2\n| caps4               = 46   | goals4         = 2\n| caps5               = 25   | goals5         = 5\n| caps6               = 12   | goals6         = 3\n| caps7               = 0    | goals7         = 0\n| caps8               = 9    | goals8         = 0\n| caps9               =      | goals9         =  \n| caps10              =      | goals10        =  \n| caps11              =      | goals11        =  \n| nationalyears1      = 2007\u2013\n| nationalteam1       = [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 5 \n| nationalgoals1      = 1\n| pcupdate            = 17 January 2017\n| ntupdate            = 17 January 2017\n}}\n'''Obadiah Danger Tarumbwa''' (born 25 November 1985 in [[Bulawayo]]) is a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[association football|football]] player who plays for [[Chicken Inn F.C.|Chicken Inn]] in the [[Zimbabwe Premier Soccer League]] as an [[attacking midfielder]].\n\n==Career==\nIn February 2008, he signed a 6-month deal with [[Belgian League|Belgian first division]] team [[Cercle Brugge]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sport.be|title=Obadiah Tarambwe Moyo|url=http://www.sport.be/fr/jupilerproleague/player.html?comp=2450&team=11245&member=21000|accessdate=2008-12-19}}</ref> At Cercle he was reunited with his former Highlanders FC colleagues [[Vusumuzi Nyoni]] and [[Honour Gombami]], by whom he was tipped to the Cercle board. He is a member of the [[Zimbabwe national football team]].\n\nHis contract with Cercle Brugge was ended on 13 March 2009. He returned to his home country and signed for [[Bantu Rovers]].\n\nOn 2 August 2012, Tarumbwa returned to his homeland having been tipped to join Dynamos of Zimbabwe, but turned down the move after failing to agree terms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsday.co.zw/article/2012-08-02-dynamos-bag-tarumbwa|title=Dynamos bag Tarumbwa - NewsDay Zimbabwe|website=www.newsday.co.zw|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref> He joined [[Cypriot Second Division]] club [[Ermis Aradippou]] and got the number 7 jersey.\n\nOn 29 December 2012, Tarumbwa landed in [[Kenya]] to sign a two-year contract with [[2009 Kenyan Premier League]] champions [[Sofapaka F.C.|Sofapaka]]. The deal was finalised on 2 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/sofapaka-land-cyprus-based-striker |title=Sofapaka land Cyprus based striker |date=2 January 2013 |author=Dan Ngulu |publisher=Futaa.com |accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.supersport.com/football/kenya/news/130103/Sofapaka_sign_Zimbabwean_hitman |title=Sofapaka sign Zimbabwean hitman |date=3 January 2013 |publisher=[[SuperSport (TV Channel)|SuperSport]].com |accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[University of Pretoria F.C.]]  during the June 2013 [[Kenya Premier League|TPL]] mid-season break\n\n==International goals==\n:''As of match played 11 June 2016. Zimbabwe score listed first, score column indicates score after each Tarumbwa goal.''<ref name=SW>{{soccerway|obidiah-tarumbwa/53549}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!scope=col|No.\n!scope=col data-sort-type=date|Date\n!scope=col|Venue\n!scope=col|Cap\n!scope=col|Opponent\n!scope=col|Score\n!scope=col|Result\n!scope=col|Competition\n|-\n!scope=row|1\n|11 June 2016||[[Sam Nujoma Stadium]], [[Windhoek]], Namibia||2||{{fb|Swaziland}}||1\u20132||2\u20132||[[2016 COSAFA Cup]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT player|pid=22291}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tarumbwa, Obadiah}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bulawayo]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwe international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Cercle Brugge K.S.V. players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Enosis Neon Paralimni FC players]]\n[[Ca